Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members of the board of the US central bank, the Federal Reserve, gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the most important central bank in the world and its future path.
The obvious question, which needs to be asked first, is how it was possible for the Fed to so glaringly miss its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Now, institutional soul-searching is certainly appropriate.
Yet while monetary policy is making headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another major question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to advance climate or social policies.
For example, the Fed could refuse to grant loans to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant loans only to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or direct lending towards desired alternatives.
Moreover, it could decide to explicitly take on regulation in the name of equality or ethnic justice by prescribing to banks where and to whom loans should be granted, who should be hired and who should be fired, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of which direction the Fed's regulation will or should move in, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In 2008, the US government made a consequential decision: financial institutions could still largely obtain money for risky investments by selling short-term, run-prone debt instruments, but hordes of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the risk exposure of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of subprime mortgage-sized liabilities in bank balance sheets.
Yet in the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred at the beginning of 2020, the Fed discarded its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even greater scale.
In March, the commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for plain-vanilla US government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed again rescued the money market funds.
Nothing is simpler to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
Moreover, the Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the rescue package for the financial sector - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
But in 2020, with the "Powell put" - among other things - an explicit floor for corporate bond prices was introduced.
The predictable reply to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to Covid-19 could certainly have caused a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the US Treasury will simply put out any new fire with a new flood of money.
Of course, the problem lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why go to the trouble of using liquidity provisions or balance sheet space for purchases at falling prices, or treating a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will inevitably outfly everyone and pocket the profits.
Why would companies still issue shares when they could simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why would investors hesitate when it comes to buying dubious papers, when their value is guaranteed in bad times by another "Whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder America is sinking into debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will cover the losses in the next downturn.
Student loans, state pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue action.
Yet every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to invest more money in rescue operations and people will not be happy with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up to a major fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulators and lawmakers at least still recognized the moral risk and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would cover the losses.
In 2020, people merely indulged in self-satisfaction regarding the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to foresee the risks of subprime mortgages just as it failed to foresee the pandemic in 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests in view of "climate risks," will certainly also overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next sovereign debt default, or another disruptive event.
The Fed regulators do not even ask the question about the mentioned events.
And although jargon about "interconnections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define the "systemic" risk at all, aside from the fact that it has become a catch-all term that grants regulatory authorities comprehensive power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to foresee risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that immense debts can always be repaid.
We must reverse the basic premise of a financial system in which the state always steps in to cover mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
Better regulation can bridge political divides.
The Left is right when it argues that large banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit few Americans.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations represents a major barrier to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is senseless.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have prophetic abilities.
The Fed scandalously stopped companies in the narrow banking and payment services sector that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it commits itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
